observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Include in the SCBAA the budget and actual amounts of Operations for Economic Enterprises;

Adjust the original and final budget amounts under GF to conform with the annual and supplemental budgets of the municipality;

Cross-reference the budgeted amounts against annual and supplemental budgets of the municipality that were enacted through appropriation ordinances in ascertaining the accuracy of the SCBAA; 

Prepare RAAOs in support of the SCBAA of the municipality; and

Provide disclosure in the NFS of the changes in the original budget.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:

GSO-Designate to:

Prepare and maintain stock cards for each type of supplies and materials for monitoring the inventory levels;

Prepare and submit on a weekly basis the required Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) with the original copies of the Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) which serve as the basis of the Municipal Accountant in recording expenses on supplies and materials in the books of accounts;

Conduct inventory count on supplies and materials, with the assistance of the different departments of the municipality, and incorporate the results of inventory count in the RPCI which will be submitted to the Municipal Accountant.

Municipal Accountant to:

Prepare and maintain Supplies Ledger Card (SLC) for each type of supplies and materials and reconcile the same regularly with the Stock Cards of the GSO;

Record the procurement of supplies and materials initially at its appropriate inventory accounts upon receipt of the documents such as Acceptance and Inspection Report, and record the issuance of supplies and materials upon receipt of the SSMI with RIS; 

Coordinate with the GSO-Designate with regard to the accountable forms, plates and stickers, office supplies, and other supplies and materials that are still unused or unissued at year-end and once the value of the inventory account is completely determined, then prepare the necessary adjusting entries on the related inventory accounts; and

Obtain a copy of the RPCI which shall be the basis in identifying any discrepancies between the inventory count and recorded values of inventory items.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, as the Head of the Procuring Entity (HOPE), direct the following:

The BAC:

Through its BAC Secretariat, prepare and send the notification of bid submission and ensure that the bidder receives the said document;

To require the winning bidder to submit Construction Safety and Health Program (CSHP) approved by the Department of Labor and Employment (DOLE) prior to the contract signing of infrastructure projects;

Through its BAC Secretariat, to ensure that all relevant documents issued to the bidder, particularly the Notice of Awards (NOAs) and Notice to Proceed (NTPs), are duly affixed with the date of receipt of the concerned bidder;

Through its BAC Secretariat, to post the NOA in the PhilGEPS website within the prescribed period;

To ensure that the bidding documents, particularly the Bid Data Sheet (BDS), Special Conditions of Contract (SCC) and Specifications are duly filled-out to define the specific undertakings of the bidders for each of the procurement projects at hand;

The BAC and its TWG to:

Judiciously conduct post-qualification proceedings by thoroughly verifying, validating and ascertaining all statements made and documents submitted by the bidder with the Lowest Calculated Bid (LCB); and

Conduct post-qualification only to the bidder with the LCB.

We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor, as HOPE, to enter into a contract with the winning bidder within 10 calendar days from receipt of the latter of the NOA to ensure timely implementation of projects and eventually, promptly benefitted its constituents.

We have recommended that the LCE direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Submit the revised Summary or a new Schedule/Report specifying the exact day and the month of the actual recognition, and the estimated useful life of each item of PPE for the Audit Team’s validation.  Submit also the necessary documents in support of the actual date of recognition;

After accomplishing the no. 1 recommendation and after the recomputation of the exact and correct Accumulated Depreciation as of December 31, 2020 and Depreciation Expense for CY 2021 by taking into consideration the discussion herein, adjust the affected accounts in accordance with applicable provisions of IPSAS using the recommended adjusting entry.

We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the:

Inventory Committee to include in the conduct of inventory the properties of the municipality, the infrastructures and other community facilities, and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System of the Local Government Unit;

GSO to render a Report on Local Road Network of the LGU at the end of the accounting period;

Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects; and

OIC – Municipal Accountant to complete the Registry of Public Infrastructure and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network to facilitate recognition in the books of accounts and disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that relevant information is supplied and available to the intended users of the financial statements, enabling them to make well-informed decisions based on a comprehensive understanding of the financial reports, henceforth:

Adequately provide a concise narrative pertaining to the amount and nature of restricted cash balances in the NFS in compliance with IPSAS 2;
Provide necessary disclosure of inventories in accordance with IPSAS 12;
Provide in the Summary of Significant Accounting Policies the estimated useful lives of each PPE classification; and
Furnish complete attachments to the Notes to PPE, presenting the reconciliation of gross carrying amounts and accumulated depreciation, with clear disclosures of additions, disposals, transfer, depreciation, and other adjustments.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
Municipal Engineer to:

institutionalize a standard mechanism for the preparation of the ABC, incorporating the specific provisions outlined in DPWH DO No. 197, series of 2016;
provide the Detailed Estimates or DUPA for the CSHP work item, ensuring alignment with the minimum OSHS requirements prescribed by the DOLE;
conduct periodic inspections to verify the contractor’s compliance with OSHS standards, and to ensure that each inspection is supported by appropriate documentation, including photographs and field reports;
BAC to thoroughly review the POW and Detailed Estimates prepared by the implementing offices and submitted by the bidders; and
Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Treasurer, to initiate the recovery of overpayments totaling ₱170,355.00 from the concerned contractors, and ensure the proper recording of the refund in the books of accounts.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, as the Chairman of the Board of Directors of the SDC instruct the Management of the Center to:
Suspend the granting and renewal of all loan releases to borrowers, due to the SDC’s unsustainable lending operations, poor collection performance, and the absence of an adequate feasibility and credit risk management framework;
Conduct a comprehensive assessment of the collectability of all past due loan accounts, determine the extent of uncollectible receivables, and develop and implement appropriate loan restructuring strategies;
Provide adequate and verifiable documents to substantiate that the ₱2.98 million was utilized for the direct benefit of tobacco farmers, in accordance with the intent and allowable purposes under RA 7171; and
Exert all lawful and enforceable measures to recover outstanding overdue accounts, including but not limited to the issuance of demand letters, and enforcement of salary deduction schemes for municipal employee-borrowers.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Require the GSO to accomplish all the necessary and relevant information required in the PO to compel the supplier to perform its obligation in accordance with the terms and conditions of the contract and impose sanctions in case of breach of contract;

Direct the BAC Secretariat to ensure that all relevant documents issued to the bidder particularly the NTP are duly affixed with the date of receipt of the concerned bidder to determine the reckoning date of the winning bidder’s responsibility in fulfilling its obligations;


Require the Municipal Accountant to:

See to it that all POs are properly accomplished before processing claims for payment of suppliers for easier determination whether or not liquidated damages are to be deducted against the claims of the supplier; and

Ensure that all documentary requirements provided under COA Circular No. 2012-001 particularly in this case, the delivery receipt, were submitted before payments are made.

