2.25     We reiterated that the Local Chief Executive instruct the:
Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical inventory and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment not later than January 31 of each year;
OIC-General Services Office (GSO) as Property Custodian to (i) maintain Property Cards for each type of property in coordination with the Municipal Accounting Office (MAO); (ii) maintain Local Road Inventory and Road Map and Local Road Network Property Card; and (iii) secure all documents or deed of donation from the donor of donated properties and furnish the Accounting a copy for proper recognition of the same in the books of accounts;
MAO to (i) prepare and maintain Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card (PPELC), Construction-in-Progress Ledger Cards (CIPLC) and Real Property Ledger Cards (RPLC); (ii) provide correct depreciation for all depreciable PPEs and draw the necessary journal entry voucher to reflect the adjustments thereof; and (iii) recognize donated properties in the books of accounts;
Municipal Engineering Office to provide the MAO and the GSO the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects as the basis of the Municipal Accountant to record the same in the books of accounts; and
Municipal Assessor to immediately survey the landholdings declared under the name of the Municipality and assist the OIC-GSO in undertaking the necessary actions for the registration and titling thereof.

We recommended that the:
Municipal Treasurer
Prepare a stratified schedule of “presumptive income level” to approximate the gross receipt of each business classification for every tax period;
Require all persons, who are granted a permit to conduct an activity or business and who are subject to payment of business tax to submit a certified photocopy of their income tax returns (ITR) on or before April 30 of each year and collect any tax deficiency, if any, including interest at the rate of ten percent (10%) corresponding to the two percent (2%) per month from January to May. Otherwise, enforce the corresponding penalty for non-compliance therewith;
Enjoin business establishments to pay taxes prior to retirement/closure;
Collect the tax deficiency from the concerned business entities; and
Enforce other remedies to ensure that the correct amount of fees and taxes are collected.
Business Permit and Licensing Officer ensure that applicants, (i) for newly started businesses or renewal of existing permits, submit a complete set of all documentary requirements in securing permits and licenses prior to the approval of the Local Chief Executive; and (ii) declare the correct amount of gross sales in their application consistent with the provision of the Updated Revenue Ordinance.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the OIC - Municipal Treasurer to:

Require the collectors to remit all collections intact and daily, prepare RCR for every remittance to be made and submit monthly individual RAAF as basis in monitoring their accountability;


Deposit all collections daily and intact;




Prepare consolidated monthly RAAF;




Comply strictly with the provisions of DOF DC No. 002-2022 dated May 16, 2022, in transacting other than authorized government depository bank.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Direct the BAC to strictly comply with the provisions of Section 17.3 and Annex C of Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 in providing ample time to prospective bidders to examine the bid documents and prepare their respective bids, hence the municipality could avail of the best offer which is more advantageous to the government;

Direct the BAC through its BAC Secretariat to send the Notification of Bid Submission and ensure that the bidder receive the said document to ensure transparency and accurate representation of the bids submitted;


Require the BAC Secretariat to ensure that all relevant documents issued to the bidder particularly the NOA and NTP are duly affixed with the date of receipt of the concerned bidder to ascertain that the perfection date of the contract and its effectivity conforms with the required time prescribed in Sections 37.2.1 and 37.4.1 of 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;

Instruct the BAC Secretariat to post the NOA in the PhilGEPS website within the prescribed period as required in Section 37.1.6 of the same Act hence, promoting transparency and efficiency in the procurement process;


Direct the BAC to ensure that all procurements made by the PE, under competitive bidding, strictly follow the proceedings of the bidding process in order to ascertain the legality and validity of contracts entered into by municipality;

Direct the BAC and its TWG to judiciously conduct post-qualification by verifying, validating and ascertaining all statements made and documents submitted by the bidder with the LCB;

Instruct the BAC Chairman to see to it that prior to contract signing of infrastructure projects, require the winning bidder to submit CSHP approved by the DOLE as mandated under Section 37.2 of 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 in order to ensure the protection and welfare of both the construction workers and general public and to avoid possible disallowance of the same;

Direct the BAC to issue Notice of Postponement in cases of rescheduled bid opening to inform prospective bidders and concerned persons of the changes made for transparency purposes; and

Direct the BAC to ensure that the bidding documents and standard forms are duly filled-out to define the specific undertakings of the bidders.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Compel the Municipal Engineer to exercise utmost prudence and diligence in her duties and responsibilities in the verification of submitted request for payment for work accomplished including SWA and other supporting documents which will be the basis of disbursements;

Direct the PMC to monitor and evaluate project implementation meticulously;


Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure completeness of supporting documents such as the approved Variation Order in cases where there are changes in the quantities of work items billed by the contractors; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant to require the contractor to refund the overpayment of work items.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the LDRMMO and MPDC to:

Identify specific PPAs in the LDRRMFIP. Identified PPAs must be backed-up with activity proposals or designs and LDRRMFIP shall include specific implementation dates;

Include PPAs to be funded under Special Trust Fund in the preparation of LDRRMFIP;


Review PPAs under Continuing Appropriations and consider reprogramming those non-specific PPAs for its implementation;

Include all identified specific PPAs in the Annual Procurement Plan;


Review Fund Utilization Reports regularly.

We have recommended that the LCE:

Facilitate the transfer of the subject parcels of land in the name of the municipality by executing a notarized deed of absolute sale or its equivalent, and other documentary requirements needed for the transfer of property;


Request the Sangguniang Bayan Members to authorize him to enter into Memorandum of Agreement with the developer;

Issue supplemental guideline specifying the timelines in the execution of the projects to provide a sense of urgency among the parties; and

Execute a memorandum of agreement or written agreement between the LGU and the developer to determine both parties’ participation in the execution/ implementation of the socialized housing.

We have recommended that the LCE direct the:

Municipal Treasurer to:

Strictly implement the provisions of the Municipal Revenue Code in order to correct the assessment and collection of business taxes that will accrue to the Municipality;


Conduct regular inspection and verification of financial records of the business establishments to ensure that the correct gross receipts will be declared by the taxpayer;

Municipal Business and Permits Licensing Office (MBPLO) to:

Refrain from accepting application for the renewal of business permits which are not based on the documentary requirements like the audited financial statements or BIR returns or sworn declaration particularly when the taxpayer submit prior year’s gross receipts in rounded figures;

Require submission of complete documentation of the financial records from taxpayers for the correct assessment of taxes; and

Maintain and use an individual ledger or index card for each business establishment in recording their payment.

We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the:
1. Inventory Committee to include in the conduct of inventory of the properties of the municipality the infrastructures and other community facilities and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of the Local Road Network System of the Local Government Unit;
2. General Services Officer (GSO) to render a Report on Local Road Network of the LGU at the end of the accounting period;
3. Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects including those implemented in the current year; and
4. OIC-Municipal Accountant to complete the Registry of Public Infrastructure and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network to facilitate recognition in the book of accounts and disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements.

We recommended that the LCE direct the Municipal Assessor and MPDC to judiciously and rigorously plan, budget and evaluate the procurement of parcel of land under the 20% DF in order to avoid the occurrence of the foregoing identified circumstances, such as conducting a feasibility study, legal and technical consultations to ensure the viability of the intended infrastructure projects in the future.
We also recommended that the LCE:
a. Facilitate the transfer of the subject parcel of lands in the name of the municipality by preparing the executing a notarized deed of absolute sale or its equivalent, and other documentary requirements needed for the transfer of property;
b. Request the Sangguniang Bayan Members to authorize him to enter into Memorandum of Agreement with the developer;
c. Issue supplemental guidelines specifying the timelines in the execution of the projects to provide a sense of urgency among the parties; and lastly
d. Execute a memorandum of agreement or written agreement between the LGU and the developer to determine both parties’ participation in the execution/implementation of the socialized housing.

We have recommended the Local Chief Executive the following:
1. Revisit the organization structure of the municipality so as to create positions which are essential in the delivery of public service to the constituents and to lessen the number of JOCs;
2. Strictly comply with the abovementioned provisions on the hiring of the JOCs.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:
Municipal Treasurer to:
Strictly implement the provisions of the Municipal Revenue Code in order to correct the assessment and collection of business taxes that will accrue to the Municipality;
Conduct regular inspection and verification of financial records of the business establishments to ensure that the correct gross receipts will be declared by the taxpayer;
Municipal Business and Permits Licensing Officer (MBPLO) to:
Refrain from accepting application for the renewal of business permits which are not based on the documentary requirements like the audited financial statements or BIR returns or sworn declaration particularly when the taxpayer submit prior year’s gross receipts in rounded figures;
Require submission of complete documentation of the financial records from taxpayers for the correct assessment of taxes; and
Maintain and use an individual ledger or index card for each business establishment in recording their tax payment.
During exit conference, the OIC-Municipal Treasurer committed to strictly adhere with the audit recommendations by undergoing tax strategies to verify the accuracy of gross sales/receipts declared by the business establishments and in case of under declaration the will reassessed and collect additional taxes.

We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) direct:
The Property Officer to maintain property cards and issue Property Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment to Accountable Officers;
the Property Officer and Municipal Accountant to investigate, correct, adjust and record the unreconciled PPE balances between the books and inventory report and undertake the procedural guidelines enumerated in COA Circular No. 2020-006 for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances to come up with more reliable account balances to be presented in the financial statements.

We have recommended that the Head of the Procuring Entity (HOPE) to direct the:
Office of the Municipal Engineer to fast track the processing of the required documents on the completed infrastructure projects to facilitate payments thereof;
BAC Chairman to:
monitor each procurement activities specified in the Annual Procurement Plan and reflect the information in the Procurement Monitoring Report as well as the timeline on all procurement activities;
prepare, consolidate and submit the required Revised Annual Procurement Plan and Procurement Monitoring Report within the prescribed submission in the GPPB Circular not only to the Department of the Interior and Local Government for the purposes of compliance report for the Seal of Good Local Governance but on the obligations of the agency on the full disclosure and sustainability of transparent practice on how the public funds are managed, disbursed and used.
Management commented that the BAC already prepared the PMR and will update it as a reference for the current year in consonance with the PPAs listed in the APP/AIP. Moreover, they are now aware on the importance of PMR as a monitoring tool for on-going and completed projects to expedite delivery and payment in order for the suppliers/contractors in incurring delays in its implementation.

We have recommended that the LCE direct the:
Municipal Accountant to:
Verify the propriety and consistency of the documents attached per Disbursement Vouchers;
Inform the corresponding preparers to scrupulously prepare the documents indicating the actual date of their preparation
Department heads to:
Judiciously plan and ascertain the anticipated events to be conducted in the ensuing calendar year and consider such in the inclusion of the procurement of meals and snacks in their preparation of PPMPs;
Prepare complete and properly filled-out PPMPs as useful basis of BAC for consolidation of APP;
Bids and Awards Committee to:
Consolidate PPMP and properly fill out the prescribed format of APP considering the requirements provided by the end user or requesting office as basis in initiating procurement activity;
Revisit the 2016 RIRR of RA No. 9184 and employ the appropriate method of procurement depending on the circumstances surrounding per transaction.
During exit conference, Management favorably accepted the observation and adhere to comply with the audit recommendation. Moreover, as to the non-inclusion of the procurement of meals and snacks in the PPMP and not undergone the procurement process, the BAC assured the audit team that they will strictly follow the procurement process. The LCE also commented that they will take necessary actions like preparing the Supplemental AIP/APP regarding the matter.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor strictly comply with the provisions of Joint Circular No. 2015-01 of the COA, DBM, DILG, Governance Commission of the GOCC, and DND on the use of Confidential Funds.
Further, we have recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Budget Officer, and other local officials concerned to:
Submit to the Audit Team, for review and verification, the disbursement voucher for the grant of cash advance for confidential expense, together with all the required and proper supporting documents, within the prescribed period pursuant to the above regulation;
Use the term Confidential Fund instead Intelligence Fund when appropriating funds for the confidential expenses under the POP of the Municipality, as appropriate only for local government units;
Strictly observe Section 6.1.5 of the Joint Circular, where cash advances should be limited to three months, and any additional amount should only be granted after the liquidation of the previous cash advances;
Process and pay claims with complete documentation only;
Submit the required quarterly report on utilization of confidential fund to the Secretary of DILG; and
Forward the Liquidation Report and supporting documents to the COA-ICFAU.

